Answer 1.1, Baseline (4p)¶

  • Dense network, at least 3 layers, shaped like a pyramid
    • Last layer: 10 nodes, sigmoid.
    • Loss: categorical cross-entropy. Metric: accuracy
  • No preprocessing, regularization. Get at least 70% accuracy.
  • Explain design decisions. Discuss performance.
    • Does it overfit (large/growing gap between loss and val_loss)?
The model first flattens the data and has 3 dense layers, using more layers seemed to yield no performance improvement (in 50 epochs). In my experience, MNIST-like classification with a dense networks, wide shallow networks work better than deeper ones. The last layer uses softmax so we get probabilites for the classification. For the other layers I use relu since it generally works well. I experimentally found the best optimizer to be (mini-batch) stochastic gradient descent.  (length: 483)

def build_model_1_1(input_shape=(32,32,3), kernel_regularizer=None):
    model_1_1 = models.Sequential()
    model_1_1.add(layers.Flatten(input_shape=input_shape))
    model_1_1.add(layers.Dense(256, kernel_regularizer=kernel_regularizer, activation='relu'))
    model_1_1.add(layers.Dense(128, kernel_regularizer=kernel_regularizer, activation='relu'))
    model_1_1.add(layers.Dense(10, kernel_regularizer=kernel_regularizer, activation='softmax'))
    model_1_1.compile(optimizer='sgd',
              loss='categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model_1_1

I turned the image into greyscale. The validation accuracy and loss converge more smoothly. Apart from this no differences were observed. Since the performance does not decrease I conclude that no crucial information was lost in the pre-processing.  (length: 250)

Answer 2.1, ConvNet (7p)¶

  • Build a sequential ConvNet, get at least 90% accuracy.
    • Conv2D layers, input shape (32,32,1)
    • Consider using blocks of Conv2D layers with maxpooling in between
    • Use zero-padding in Conv2D layers because the images are small
    • At least one dense hidden layer and dense output layer (sigmoid)
    • Consider adding batch normalization, dropout
    • Consider small dropout rates in beginning, larger dropout rates later in network
    • Consider other optimizers and tuning learning rate, momentum,...
  • Explain what you did and why (800 chars). Is it working well?
    • Should be quite elaborate and sensible
We start with a VGG-like network with MaxPooling to keep the amount of weights in check. Padding is used to prevent the layers from shrinking too much. MaxPooling is used to prevent the feature space from exploding. This network reached a training accuracy of 1.0 around epoch 40 which implied overfitting. To counter the overfitting dropout layers were introduced after the Pooling and dense layers. We also apply BatchNormalization to prevent internal covariate shift. Performance flatlines quite quickly. The very high dropouts seemed to work best.  (length: 553)

def build_model_2_1():
    model_2_1 = models.Sequential()
    model_2_1.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=(32,32,1)))
    model_2_1.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model_2_1.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model_2_1.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model_2_1.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
    model_2_1.add(layers.Dropout(0.3))
    model_2_1.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model_2_1.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model_2_1.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model_2_1.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model_2_1.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
    model_2_1.add(layers.Dropout(0.4))
    model_2_1.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model_2_1.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model_2_1.add(layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model_2_1.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model_2_1.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
    model_2_1.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))
    model_2_1.add(layers.Flatten())
    model_2_1.add(layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'))
    model_2_1.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
    model_2_1.add(layers.Dropout(0.55))
    model_2_1.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
    model_2_1.compile(optimizer='sgd', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model_2_1

Answer 2.2, Data Augmentation (3p)¶

  • Augment the preprocessed training data.
    • Use small variations (small shifts up-down, left-right) of flips becasue the images are small
    • Large shifts and rotations distort the image too much
  • Explain what you did and why. Discuss the performance of the model.
Since the streetview pictures are taken from different angles at different distances and because of the inherent variability in street number styles we help the model generalize by rotating, shearing, zooming and vertically shifting the images. Note that we do not horizontally shift the images since there are often digits side by side and we do not want the model to become confused as to which digit should be classified. We have sadly not foud a permutation of these settings that improves the final performance. However the network does converge faster with the augmented data.  (length: 584)

def build_model_4_1():
    # get VGG model
    base_model = VGG16(include_top=False, weights='imagenet', input_shape=(32, 32, 3))
    
    for layer in base_model.layers[:-4]:
        layer.trainable = False
        
    output = base_model.output
    output = layers.Flatten()(output)
    output = layers.Dropout(0.5)(output)
    output = layers.Dense(128, activation='relu')(output)
    output = layers.Dropout(0.5)(output)
    output = layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax')(output)
    
    model_4_1 = Model(inputs=base_model.input, outputs=output)
#     optimizer = 
    model_4_1.compile(optimizer='sgd', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])#0.9 0.001
    return model_4_1
